column518: In November of 2014, we closed the main library at 10 Elm Street for an extensive mold remediation/repair project. We relocated all library services to an offsite location (formerly a library branch, but vacant since 2009), which was open to the public from mid-November until the end of January. In addition, we closed for two weeks on either end to pack and move. The alternate location was significantly smaller; we were only able to bring about a third of our regular collection during this time, while the remaining collection was unavailable to our patrons, and the rest of our Consortium, for over three months. Also, the temporary location offered no programming space, so the few programs we maintained had to be done off-site. The 4 weeks of total closure during the project -- coupled with the staff time that was redirected from normal tasks to managing the project -- resulted in significantly lower circulation, reference, and program numbers during this period of time.

column518: FY13 was a difficult year for our library, and we are still feeling the repercussions. We lost our longtime Director, and hired a new short-lived Director who lost the confidence of many of our patrons. Staffing issues coinciding with the new Director and the absence before she was replaced meant that our services (such as ILL and reference) were not at the same level they once were (since we relied so heavily on volunteers) and we also lost patrons this way. It has been a long process trying to regain standing in our community, though this year shows signs of improvement. We have a new Director who is here for the long-term and who has made great strides in making the library the center of the community again.

column2: West Springfield - West Springfield Public Library
column518: The West Springfield Public Library is in the midst of a construction and renovation project. We closed to the public at 5 p.m. on Saturday, February 15th and did not reopen until Monday, March 17th. Although we secured a wonderful space for the temporary library and were able to make our entire collection available, we have not returned to normal service levels. Our Circulation numbers for the Fiscal Year ending 2014, were down 23.75% One immediate consequence of the move into a two-story building was to have more staff covering in the evenings. Hence, we now close at 5 p.m. on Thursdays in order to have a minimum of five staff members in the building at night. Aside from the move, the library lost 13 hours due to inclement weather, and one hour due to a power outage.
